    Let two matrices be

    A=[4369],                    B=[−29−52] A =

    , \;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\;\; B =
    [−2−592]

    Correct

    To subtract B from A, carry out the subtraction element-wise.

    5.

    Question 5

    Let A and B be 3x3 (square) matrices. Which of the following

    must necessarily hold true? Check all that apply.

    1 / 1 point
    Correct

    Even though matrix multiplication is not commutative in general (A∗B≠B∗AA*B \neq B*AA∗B​=B∗A for general matrices A,BA, BA,B), for the special case where B=IB=IB=I, we have A∗B=A∗I=AA*B = A*I = AA∗B=A∗I=A, and also B∗A=I∗A=AB*A = I*A = AB∗A=I∗A=A. So, A∗B=B∗AA*B = B*AA∗B=B∗A.

    Correct

    Since A and B are both 3x3 matrices, their product is 3x3. More generally, if A were an m×nm \times nm×n. matrix, and B a n×on\times on×o matrix, then C would be m×om\times om×o. (In our example, m=n=o=3m=n=o=3m=n=o=3.)
